  5.1 Visualization algorithm
  It is well known that the symmetric KL divergence between
  Gaussians does not satisfy the requirements to a proper dis-
  tance measure \[12\]. Therefore, we use a visualization tech-
  nique that seeks to preserve the KL divergence values in
  a low-dimensional visualization space and relaxes this de-
  mand if that is not possible. A classic distance-preserving
  data mining/visualization technique is Multidimensional Scal-
  ing \[4\], which aims at placing data points in low dimen-
  sional visualization space while approximating the distances
  in feature space as closely as possible. Multidimensional
  scaling can be implemented as a spring model \[2, 11\], a
  physically inspired model of spring-connected nodes aiming
  at finding a node placement that minimizes the cumulative
  deflection from the springs’ resting states. By mapping dis-
  tances in feature space to spring lengths, the spring model
  solves the MDS problem approximately.
  We chose to use a spring model variant of MDS because
  of its ease of implementation and because of the attractive
  visualizations that can be generated by constantly drawing
  the gradual relaxation of the system. By using a gradient-
  descent based solution algorithm (see algorithm 1), a place-
  ment of the nodes that minimizes the overall stress (the de-
  flection from the springs’ resting state) is constructed.
  While the overall stress in the model (S
  cum
  ) is larger than
  a threshold (S
  thresh
