  5.2 Features from the spikegram
  The input of the classifier needs to be a feature vector of
  fixed size for every segment of a song (5seconds segments
  here). Of course, a sparse code is designed to adapt to
  specific audio signals. The number of spikes per segment
  changes, and the spikes can be positioned at any given mu-
  sic frame. Thus we have encode the information about the
  spikes differently in order to use it as input to a typical clas-
  sifier.
  Here we try two types of features based on the spikes.
  First, we simply count the number of times each spike is
  used in every segment, and we also sum their scaling coeffi-
  cientss. We also give the same information, but normalized
  by the number of spikes in the segment. Finally, we give the
  classifier the total number of spikes in this segment. For64
  kernels, this yields an input vector of size257per segment.
