  at a cut off of 20 documents).
  To ease the comparison of our approach with the state-of-
  the-art, we have implemented one of the most popular tim-
  bre similarity measure based on spectral shape features. It
  simply consists of a Mel-Frequency Cepstrum Coefficients
  (MFCCs) frame-based parameterization of the audio signal
  (20 coefficients including the energy coefficient). These
  features are aggregated over the song as a Gaussian with
  full covariance matrix and compared using the symmetric
  version of the Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence. This ap-
  proach has been originally introduced by Mandel and El-
  lis \[10\] and was used in the winning algorithm of the 1st
  Annual Music Information Retrieval Evaluation exchange
