  The experiment was, then, to explore the data set we had
  acquired, verifying if patterns from this catalogue could be
  found in the data set. For the experiment the algorithm
  FlExPat \[8\] was chosen. It is an inexact string matching
  algorithm that was inspired by algorithms from the Com-
  putational Biology field, but that also incorporates results
  from previous research on musical similarity \[7\]. Given an
  input (here the simplified string previously described) and
  using the edit distance as its similarity measure
  9
  , the algo-
  rithm outputs a collection of patterns, organized in classes.
  Each class has a prototype, that is the most representative
  pattern of the class, and several occurrences, possibly inex-
  act, of this prototype. It is also possible for the user to pro-
  vide the algorithm with some constraints, such as the maxi-
  mal and minimal length of patterns, the similarity threshold,
  the maximum difference between two candidates to be com-
  pared, etc.
